Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Eveready East Africa Falls to Lowest on Record

-- B y   S a r a h   M c G r e g o r
-- 
2011-04-26T15:51:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-26/sub-saharan-african-stocks-eveready-east-africa-falls-to-lowest-on-record.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index advanced
for the third consecutive trading day, climbing 0.1 percent to
close at 75.03 by 3 p.m. in Nairobi.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index strengthened for a
second day, gaining 1.1 percent to 1,094.17 by 3:16 p.m. in
Accra. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose less than 0.1 percent to
2,058.02 at the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  dropped 0.3 percent to
873.45 by the close in Windhoek. Nigeria’s stock market was
closed for gubernatorial and legislative elections.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Eveready East Africa Ltd. (EVRD)  , a Kenyan dry-cell
battery maker, fell to its lowest on record as investors
speculated its earnings would continue to be hurt by counterfeit
products.  The stock dropped as much as 20 cents, or 9.1 percent, to
2.15 shillings, the lowest since at least February 2007, when
Bloomberg began tracking the company’s shares. It closed down
2.3 percent at 2.15 shillings, bringing its decline this year to
28 percent.  Standard Chartered Bank Ghana Ltd. (SCB GN), the Ghanaian
lender, jumped to a record after announcing it will issue at
least five bonus shares for every one held by investors at the
end of 2012, as part of a plan to increase the bank’s issued
share capital to 100 million.  The stock advanced 3.01 cedis, or 5.8 percent, to 55.01
cedis.  To contact the reporters on this story:
